<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="766" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="163.[1444,2651,1047,1672]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1446,1694,1047,1081]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
This species and the East African Thicket Rat (G. beanus) are the largest members of genus. The Mozambique Thicket Rat has head-body 112-124 mm, tail 142-194 mm, ear 17-20 mm, hindfoot 23-25 mm; weight c.52 g. Fur is short,silky, and reddish brown above, with sharply demarcated pure white belly. Tail is very long (120-160% of head-body length) and semi-prehensile, with terminal tuft of hairs. Ears usually have a white post-auricular spot. There are four digits on forefoot and five digits on relatively short hindfoot, thefifth digit longer and semi-opposable. Females have either 0+2 = 2 or 142 = 3 pairs of nipples. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 52, FN = 62.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
